Introduction of KNN Algorithm¶

  1. K-Nearest Neighbour is one of the simplest Machine Learning algorithms based on Supervised Learning technique.

  2. K-NN algorithm assumes the similarity between the new case/data and available cases and put the new case into the category that is most similar to the available categories.

  3. K-NN algorithm stores all the available data and classifies a new data point based on the similarity. This means when new data appears then it can be easily classified into a well suite category by using K- NN algorithm.
  4. K-NN algorithm can be used for Regression as well as for Classification but mostly it is used for the Classification problems.
  5. K-NN is a non-parametric algorithm, which means it does not make any assumption on underlying data.
  6. It is also called a lazy learner algorithm because it does not learn from the training set immediately instead it stores the dataset and at the time of classification, it performs an action on the dataset.
  7. KNN algorithm at the training phase just stores the dataset and when it gets new data, then it classifies that data into a category that is much similar to the new data.
  8. Example: Suppose, we have an image of a creature that looks similar to cat and dog, but we want to know either it is a cat or dog. So for this identification, we can use the KNN algorithm, as it works on a similarity measure. Our KNN model will find the similar features of the new data set to the cats and dogs images and based on the most similar features it will put it in either cat or dog category

Source : Java T point

How does K-NN work?¶

The K-NN working can be explained on the basis of the below algorithm:

Step-1: Select the number K of the neighbors

Step-2: Calculate the Euclidean distance of K number of neighbors

Step-3: Take the K nearest neighbors as per the calculated Euclidean distance.

Step-4: Among these k neighbors, count the number of the data points in each category.

Step-5: Assign the new data points to that category for which the number of the neighbor is maximum.

Step-6: Our model is ready

Source : Java T point

Some points about KNN¶

  1. Distance is the most important parameter.

  2. Each of the training data consists of a label data association with it, either +ive or -ive. Although, KNN also supports multiclass classification.

  3. We are also given a single number k this number decides how many neighbors influence the classification. This is usually a odd number.

  4. We will calculate the Euclidean distance between the data points. The Euclidean distance is the distance between two points, which we have already studied in geometry. It can be calculated as:

If we see above two "Age" & "EstimitedSalary" column then there is a huge difference between these numbers. Here is the age which is roughly in the range of 18-70 & salary in the range of thousand.

In KNN we should need to findout the square of the distance between these two numbers.

If we are going to findout the square distance between Age & Salary then it will be the huge number. So, it will highly impact on our result.

What we can do? We should need to scale down the value of Salary column which is same as the value of Age column.

For that we use one python library named as sklearn

def predict_output():
  age=int(input("Enter the age :"))
  salary=int(input("Enter your salary : "))

  # we will convert these two values into numpy array
  # we creating numpy array because these are my inputs for my classifier 
  # And we already know when you provide an input it should be need to in 2-D matrix

  return np.array([[age],[salary]]).shape

If you remember our shape of x_train or x_test is (something,2) which means we should need 2 columns but in our case our output shape is (2,1) which have only 1 columns So, what should we do? For that we rewrite the above code again and reshaping the shape of our numpy array

In [39]:
def predict_output():
  age=int(input("Enter the age :"))
  salary=int(input("Enter your salary : "))

  # Reshaping the numpy array from (2,1) to (1,2) & store it in new variable

  x_new=np.array([[age],[salary]]).reshape(1,2)

  # Now we scale down the salary of in the range of age
  # which we already learn in same way we also do here
  
  x_new=scalar.transform(x_new)
  
  if knn.predict(x_new)[0]==0:
    return "Will not purchase"

  else:
    return "Will purchase"
